# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: software-composition-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The **Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures** (**CVE**) system, originally **Common Vulnerability Enumeration**, provides a reference method for publicly known information-security vulnerabilities and exposures.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The United States' Homeland Security Systems Engineering and Development Institute FFRDC, operated by The MITRE Corporation, maintains the system, with funding from the US National Cyber Security Division of the US Department of Homeland Security.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The system was officially launched for the public in September 1999.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The Security Content Automation Protocol uses CVE, and CVE IDs are listed on MITRE's system as well as the basis for the US National Vulnerability Database.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] MITRE Corporation's documentation defines CVE Identifiers (also called "CVE names", "CVE numbers", "CVE-IDs", and "CVEs") as unique, common identifiers for publicly known information-security vulnerabilities in publicly released software packages.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Historically, CVE identifiers originally had a status of "candidate" ("CAN-") and could then be promoted to entries ("CVE-"), but this practice was ended in 2005 and all identifiers are now assigned as CVEs.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The assignment of a CVE number is not a guarantee that it will become an official CVE entry (e.g., a CVE may be improperly assigned to an issue which is not a security vulnerability, or which duplicates an existing entry).
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] If found not to meet criteria, MITRE or a CVE Numbering Authority (CNA) can summarily place the entry into REJECTED status.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] CVEs are assigned by a CVE Numbering Authority (CNA).
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] While some vendors acted as a CNA before, the name and designation was not created until 1 February 2005.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Researchers, in one case, have been granted the CNA role.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] When investigating a vulnerability or potential vulnerability it helps to acquire a CVE number early on.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The benefit of early CVE candidacy is that all future correspondence and coordination can refer to the CVE number to ensure all parties are referring to the same vulnerability.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Information on getting CVE identifiers for issues with open source projects is available from Red Hat and GitHub.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] CVEs are for software that has been publicly released; this can include betas and other pre-release versions if they are widely used.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Commercial software is included in the "publicly released" category, but custom-built software that is not distributed would historically not be given a CVE.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] For the first two decades of the program, services (e.g., a Web-based email provider) are not assigned CVEs for vulnerabilities found in the service (e.g., an XSS vulnerability) unless the issue exists in an underlying software product that is publicly distributed.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Official rules have not been published regarding this change but some CNAs including MITRE have begun assigning CVEs to service-based vulnerabilities as far back as 2000.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] This is a standardized text description of the issue(s).
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] This means that the entry number has been reserved by Mitre for an issue or a CNA has reserved the number.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] So when a CNA requests a block of CVE numbers in advance (e.g., Red Hat currently requests CVEs in blocks of 500), the CVE number will be marked as reserved even though the CVE itself may not be assigned by the CNA for some time.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Until the CVE is assigned, Mitre is made aware of it (i.e., the embargo passes and the issue is made public), and Mitre has researched the issue and written a description of it, entries will show up as "** RESERVED **".
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] For CVEs assigned directly by Mitre, this is the date Mitre created the CVE entry.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] For CVEs assigned by CNAs (e.g., Microsoft, Oracle, HP, Red Hat) this is also the date that was created by Mitre, not by the CNA.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] When a CNA requests a block of CVE numbers in advance, the entry date is when the block was assigned to the CNA.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The following fields were previously used in CVE records, but are no longer used.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] In order to support CVE IDs beyond CVE-YEAR-9999 (an issue known as the 'CVE10k problem') a change was made to the CVE syntax in 2014 and took effect on 13 January 2015.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The variable-length arbitrary digits begin at four fixed digits and expand with arbitrary digits only when needed in a calendar year; for example, CVE-YYYY-NNNN and if needed CVE-YYYY-NNNNN, CVE-YYYY-NNNNNN, and so on.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The schema is compatible with previously assigned CVE-IDs, which all include a minimum of four digits.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The Mitre CVE database can be searched at the CVE List Search, and the NVD CVE database can be searched at Search CVE and CCE Vulnerability Database.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Users who have been assigned a CVE identifier for a vulnerability are encouraged to ensure that they place the identifier in any related security reports, web pages, emails, and so on.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Per section 7 of the CNA Rules, a vendor which received a report about a security vulnerability has full discretion in regards to it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] This can lead to a conflict of interest as a vendor may attempt to leave flaws unpatched by denying a CVE assignment at first place – a decision which Mitre can't reverse.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The "!CVE" (not CVE) project, announced in 2023, aims to collect vulnerabilities that are denied by vendors, so long as they are considered valid by a panel of experts from the project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] CVE identifiers have been awarded for bogus issues and issues without security consequences.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] In response, a number of open-source projects have themselves applied to become the CVE Numbering Authority (CNA) of their own project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] On 15 April 2025, it was reported that the contract between MITRE and the US government, set to expire the day after, would be allowed to expire.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Reports stated that the expiration of the contract would bring an end to the operational arm of the CVE program, including assigning new CVEs, while the database would remain accessible via GitHub.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Just prior to its expiration, the contract was extended for 11 months, averting the shutdown of the program.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Following the risk of funding expiration on March 16, 2026, the acting director of CISA Nick Andersen stated that the program is now being fully funded.
[src:software-composition-analysis/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Pete Allor, the co-founder of CVE Foundation, reported that the CVE programs funding had been restructured from a discretionary item to being one of the core programs to be funded.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open-source software development can bring in diverse perspectives beyond those of a single company.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] A 2024 estimate of the value of open-source software to firms is $8.8 trillion, as firms would need to spend 3.5 times the amount they currently do without the use of open source software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] OSI uses *The Open Source Definition* to determine whether it considers a software license open source.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The definition was based on the Debian Free Software Guidelines, written and adapted primarily by Bruce Perens.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Perens did not base his writing on the "four freedoms" from the Free Software Foundation (FSF), which were only widely available later.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Under Perens' definition, *open source* is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] It is an explicit "feature" of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Despite initially accepting it, Richard Stallman of the FSF now flatly opposes the term "Open Source" being applied to what they refer to as "free software".
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe "almost the same category of software", Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Stallman also opposes the professed pragmatism of the Open Source Initiative, as he fears that the free software ideals of freedom and community are threatened by compromising on the FSF's idealistic standards for software freedom.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite that it does not give its users freedom (it restricts them), and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In his 1997 essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*, open-source influential contributor Eric S.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Raymond suggests a model for developing OSS known as the *bazaar* model.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Raymond likens the development of software by traditional methodologies to building a cathedral, with careful isolated work by individuals or small groups.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] He suggests that all software should be developed using the bazaar style, with differing agendas and approaches.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In the traditional model of development, which he called the *cathedral* model, development takes place in a centralized way.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Roles include people dedicated to designing (the architects), people responsible for managing the project, and people responsible for implementation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Traditional software engineering follows the cathedral model.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The bazaar model, however, is different.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In this model, roles are not clearly defined.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The process of Open source development begins with a requirements elicitation where developers consider if they should add new features or if a bug needs to be fixed in their project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] This is established by communicating with the OSS community through avenues such as bug reporting and tracking or mailing lists and project pages.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Next, OSS developers select or are assigned to a task and identify a solution.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Because there are often many different possible routes for solutions in OSS, the best solution must be chosen with careful consideration and sometimes even peer feedback.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The developer then begins to develop and commit the code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The code is then tested and reviewed by peers.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Developers can edit and evolve their code through feedback from continuous integration.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Once the leadership and community are satisfied with the whole project, it can be partially released and user instruction can be documented.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] If the project is ready to be released, it is frozen, with only serious bug fixes or security repairs occurring.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Finally, the project is fully released and only changed through minor bug fixes.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source implementation of a standard can increase the adoption and long-term viability of that standard.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] It often fosters developer loyalty, as contributors feel a greater sense of participation and ownership in the development process and the end product.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Moreover, lower costs of marketing and logistical services are needed for OSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] OSS can be a tool to promote a company's image, including its commercial products.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The OSS development approach has been known to some to help produce reliable, high quality software quickly and inexpensively.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source development offers the potential to quicken innovation and create social value.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In France, for instance, a policy that incentivized government to favor free open-source software increased to nearly 600,000 OSS contributions per year, generating social value by increasing the quantity and quality of open-source software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] This policy also led to an estimated increase of up to 18% of tech startups and a 14% increase in the number of people employed in the IT sector.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] OSS can be highly reliable when it has thousands of independent programmers testing and fixing bugs of the software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source is not dependent on the company or author that originally created it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Even if the company fails, the code continues to exist and be developed by its users.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] OSS is flexible as modular systems allow programmers to build custom interfaces or add new abilities to it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The mix of divergent perspectives, corporate objectives, and personal goals allows innovation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Moreover, free software can be developed in accordance with purely technical requirements.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] It does not require thinking about commercial pressure that often degrades the quality of the software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Commercial pressures make traditional software developers pay more attention to customers' requirements than to security requirements, since such features are somewhat invisible to the customer.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In open-source software development, tools are used to support the development of the product and the development process itself.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Version control systems such as Centralized Version control system (CVCS) and the distributed version control system (DVCS) are examples of tools, often open source, that help manage the source code files and the changes to those files for a software project in order to foster collaboration.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] CVCS are centralized with a central repository while DVCS are decentralized and have a local repository for every user.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Concurrent Versions System (CVS) and later Subversion (SVN) are examples of CVCS, whereas Git is a DVCS and the most widely used version control software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The repositories are hosted and published on source-code-hosting facilities such as GitHub or Gitlab.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open-source projects use utilities such as issue trackers to organize open-source software development.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Commonly used bug trackers include Bugzilla and Redmine.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Tools such as mailing lists and IRC provide means of coordination and discussion of bugs among developers.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Project web pages, wiki pages, roadmap lists and newsgroups allow for the distribution of project information that focuses on end users.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The basic roles OSS participants can fall into multiple categories, beginning with leadership at the center of the project who have control over its execution.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Next are the core contributors with a great deal of experience and authority in the project who may guide the other contributors.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Non-core contributors have less experience and authority, but regularly contribute and are vital to the project's development.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] New contributors are the least experienced but with mentorship and guidance can become regular contributors.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Some possible ways of contributing to open-source software include such roles as programming, maintaining, user interface design and testing, web design, bug triage, accessibility design and testing, UX design, code testing, and security review and testing.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, there are several ways of contributing to OSS projects even without coding skills.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, some less technical ways of participating are documentation writing and editing, translation, project management, event organization and coordination, marketing, release management, community management, and public relations and outreach.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Funding is another way that individuals and organizations choose to contribute to open source projects.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Groups like Open Collective provide a means for individuals to contribute monthly to supporting their favorite projects.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Organizations like the Sovereign Tech Fund is able to contribute to millions to supporting the tools the German Government uses.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The National Science Foundation established a Pathways to Enable Open-Source Ecosystems (POSE) program to support open source innovation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The adoption of open-source software by industry is increasing over time.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] OSS is popular in several industries such as telecommunications, aerospace, healthcare, and media & entertainment due to the benefits it provides.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Adoption of OSS is more likely in larger organizations and is dependent on the company's IT usage, operating efficiencies, and the productivity of employees.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Industries are likely to use OSS due to back-office functionality, sales support, research and development, software features, quick deployment, portability across platforms and avoidance of commercial license management.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Additionally, lower cost for hardware and ownership are also important benefits.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Organizations that contribute to the development and expansions of free and open-source software movements exist all over the world.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] These organizations are dedicated to goals such as teaching and spreading technology.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] As listed by a former vice president of the Open Source Initiative, some American organizations include the Free Software Foundation, Software Freedom Conservancy, the Open Source Initiative and Software in the Public Interest.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Within Europe some notable organizations are Free Software Foundation Europe, open-source projects EU (OSP) and OpenForum Europe (OFE).
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] One Australian organization is Linux Australia while Asia has Open source Asia and FOSSAsia.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Free and open source software for Africa (FOSSFA) and OpenAfrica are African organizations and Central and South Asia has such organizations as FLISOL and GRUP de usuarios de software libre Peru.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Outside of these, many more organizations dedicated to the advancement of open-source software exist.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] FOSS products are generally licensed under two types of licenses: permissive licensing and copyleft licensing.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Both of these types of licenses are different than proprietary licensing in that they can allow more users access to the software and allow for the creation of derivative works as specified by the terms of the specific license, as each license has its own rules.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Permissive licenses allow recipients of the software to implement the author's copyright rights without having to use the same license for distribution.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the BSD, MIT, and Apache licenses.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Copyleft licenses are different in that they require recipients to use the same license for at least some parts of the distribution of their works.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Strong copyleft licenses require all derivative works to use the same license while weak copyleft licenses require the use of the same license only under certain conditions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the GNU family of licenses, and the MPL and EPL licenses.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The similarities between these two categories of licensing include that they provide a broad grant of copyright rights, require that recipients preserve copyright notices, and that a copy of the license is provided to recipients with the code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] One important legal precedent for open-source software was created in 2008, when the Jacobson v Katzer case enforced terms of the Artistic license, including attribution and identification of modifications.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The ruling of this case cemented enforcement under copyright law when the conditions of the license were not followed.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Because of the similarity of the Artistic license to other open-source software licenses, the ruling created a precedent that applied widely.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Examples of free-software license / open-source licenses include Apache licenses, BSD licenses, GNU General Public Licenses, GNU Lesser General Public License, MIT License, Eclipse Public License and Mozilla Public License.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Several gray areas exist within software regulation that have great impact on open-source software, such as if software is a good or service, what can be considered a modification, governance through contract vs license, ownership and right of use.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] While there have been developments on these issues, they often lead to even more questions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The existence of these uncertainties in regulation has a negative impact on industries involved in technologies as a whole.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Within the legal history of software as a whole, there was much debate on whether to protect it as intellectual property under patent law, copyright law or establishing a unique regulation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Ultimately, copyright law became the standard with computer programs being considered a form of literary work, with some tweaks of unique regulation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Software is generally considered source code and object code, with both being protectable, though there is legal variety in this definition.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Some jurisdictions attempt to expand or reduce this conceptualization for their own purposes.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, The European Court of Justice defines a computer program as not including the functionality of a program, the programming language, or the format of data files.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] By limiting protections of the different aspects of software, the law favors an open-source approach to software use.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The US especially has an open approach to software, with most open-source licenses originating there.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, this has increased the focus on patent rights within these licenses, which has seen backlash from the OSS community, who prefer other forms of IP protection.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Another issue includes technological protection measures (TPM) and digital rights management (DRM) techniques which were internationally legally recognized and protected in the 1996 World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) Treaty.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source software proponents disliked these technologies as they constrained end-users potentially beyond copyright law.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Europe responded to such complaints by putting TPM under legal controls, representing a victory for OSS supporters.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In open-source communities, instead of owning the software produced, the producer owns the development of the evolving software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In this way, the future of the software is open, making ownership or intellectual property difficult within OSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Licensing and branding can prevent others from stealing it, preserving its status as a public good.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source software can be considered a public good as it is available to everyone and does not decrease in value for others when downloaded by one person.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source software is unique in that it becomes more valuable as it is used and contributed to, instead of diminishing the resource.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] This is explained by concepts such as investment in reputation and network effects.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The economic model of open-source software can be explained as developers contribute work to projects, creating public benefits.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Developers choose projects based on the perceived benefits or costs, such as improved reputation or value of the project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The motivations of developers can come from many different places and reasons, but the important takeaway is that money is not the only or even most important incentivization.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Because economic theory mainly focuses on the consumption of scarce resources, the OSS dynamic can be hard to understand.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In OSS, producers become consumers by reaping the rewards of contributing to a project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, a developer becomes well regarded by their peers for a successful contribution to an OSS project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The social benefits and interactions of OSS are difficult to account for in economic models as well.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Furthermore, the innovation of technology creates constantly changing value discussions and outlooks, making economic model unable to predict social behavior.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Although OSS is theoretically challenging in economic models, it is explainable as a sustainable social activity that requires resources.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] These resources include time, money, technology and contributions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Many developers have used technology funded by organizations such as universities and governments, though these same organizations benefit from the work done by OSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] As OSS grows, hybrid systems containing OSS and proprietary systems are becoming more common.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Throughout the mid 2000s, more and more tech companies have begun to use OSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, Dell's move of selling computers with Linux already installed.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Microsoft itself has launched a Linux-based operating system despite previous animosity with the OSS movement.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Despite these developments, these companies tend to only use OSS for certain purposes, leading to worries that OSS is being taken advantage of by corporations and not given anything in return.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, an issue to be considered is cybersecurity.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] While accidental vulnerabilities are possible, so are attacks by outside agents.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Because of these fears, governmental interest in contributing to the governance of software has become more prominent.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, these are the broad strokes of the issue, with each country having their own specific politicized interactions with open-source software and their goals for its implementation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] These criteria include whether it comes from and is maintained by trusted sources, whether it will continue to be maintained, if there are dependencies on sub-components in the software, component security and integrity, and foreign governmental influence.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Another issue for governments in regard to open source is their investments in technologies such as operating systems, semiconductors, cloud, and artificial intelligence.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] These technologies all have implications for global cooperation, again opening up security issues and political consequences.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Many countries have to balance technological innovation with technological dependence in these partnerships.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, after China's open-source dependent company Huawei was prevented from using Google's Android system in 2019, they began to create their own alternative operating system: Harmony OS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Germany recently established a Sovereign Tech Fund, to help support the governance and maintenance of the software that they use.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In the early days of computing, particularly during the 1950s and 1960s, programmers and developers commonly shared software to learn from one another and advance the field.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Early systems such as Unix even provided users with access to their source code, allowing collaboration and modification.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, with the rise of the commercial software industry in the 1970s and 1980s, this culture of open sharing began to decline as proprietary models became dominant.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Despite this shift, academic and research institutions continued to promote collaborative software development practices.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In response, the open-source movement was born out of the work of skilled programmer enthusiasts, widely referred to as hackers or hacker culture.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] One of these enthusiasts, Richard Stallman, was a driving force behind the free software movement, which would later allow for the open-source movement.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In 1984, he resigned from MIT to create a free operating system, GNU, after the programmer culture in his lab was stifled by proprietary software preventing source code from being shared and improved upon.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] GNU was UNIX compatible, meaning that the programmer enthusiasts would still be familiar with how it worked.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, it quickly became apparent that there was some confusion with the label Stallman had chosen of free software, which he described as free as in free speech, not free beer, referring to the meaning of free as freedom rather than price.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] He later expanded this concept of freedom to the four essential freedoms.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Through GNU, open-source norms of incorporating others' source code, community bug fixes and suggestions of code for new features appeared.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In 1985, Stallman founded the Free Software Foundation (FSF) to promote changes in software and to help write GNU.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In order to prevent his work from being used in proprietary software, Stallman created the concept of copyleft, which allowed the use of his work by anyone, but under specific terms.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] To do this, he created the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL) in 1989, which was updated in 1991.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In 1991, GNU was combined with the Linux kernel written by Linus Torvalds, as a kernel was missing in GNU.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The operating system is now usually referred to as Linux.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] As free software developed, the Free Software Foundation began to look how to bring free software ideas and perceived benefits to the commercial software industry.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] It was concluded that FSF's social activism was not appealing to companies and they needed a way to rebrand the free software movement to emphasize the business potential of sharing and collaborating on software source code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The term open source was suggested by Christine Peterson in 1998 at a meeting of supporters of free software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Many in the group felt the name free software was confusing to newcomers and holding back industry interest and they readily accepted the new designation of open source, creating the Open Source Initiative (OSI) and the OSI definition of what open source software is.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is now recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The OSI definition differed from the free software definition in that it allows the inclusion of proprietary software and allows more liberties in its licensing.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Some, such as Stallman, agree more with the original concept of free software as a result because it takes a strong moral stance against proprietary software, though there is much overlap between the two movements in terms of the operation of the software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, while free and open-source software (FOSS) has historically played a role outside of mainstream private software development, companies as large as Microsoft have begun to develop official open source presences on the Internet.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] IBM, Oracle, and State Farm are just a few of the companies with a serious public stake in today's competitive open source market, marking a significant shift in the corporate philosophy concerning the development of FOSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The future of the open source software community, and the free software community by extension, has become successful if not confused about what it stands for.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, Android and Ubuntu are examples milestones of success in the open source software rise to prominence from the sidelines of technological innovation as it existed in the early 2000s.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The use of OSS has become more common in business with 78% of companies reporting that they run all or part of their operations on FOSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The popularity of OSS has risen to the point that Microsoft, a once detractor of OSS, has included its use in their systems.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, this success has raised concerns that will determine the future of OSS as the community must answer questions such as what OSS is, what should it be, and what should be done to protect it, if it even needs protecting.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] All in all, while the free and open source revolution has slowed to a perceived equilibrium in the market place, that does not mean it is over as many theoretical discussions must take place to determine its future.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source software differs from proprietary software in that it is publicly available, the license requires no fees, modifications and distributions are allowed under license specifications.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] All of this works to prevent a monopoly on any OSS product, which is a goal of proprietary software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Proprietary software limits their customers' choices to either committing to using that software, upgrading it or switching to other software, forcing customers to have their software preferences impacted by their monetary cost.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The ideal case scenario for the proprietary software vendor would be a lock-in, where the customer does not or cannot switch software due to these costs and continues to buy products from that vendor.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Within proprietary software, bug fixes can only be provided by the vendor, moving platforms requires another purchase and the existence of the product relies on the vendor, who can discontinue it at any point.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Additionally, proprietary software does not provide its source code and cannot be altered by users.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For businesses, this can pose a security risk and source of frustration, as they cannot specialize the product to their needs, and there may be hidden threats or information leaks within the software that they cannot access or change.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Under OSI's definition, open source is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] It is an explicit feature of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Richard Stallman, leader of the Free software movement and member of the free software foundation opposes the term open source being applied to what they refer to as free software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe almost the same category of software, Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] He believes that the main difference is that by choosing one term over the other lets others know about what one's goals are: development (open source) or a social stance (free software).
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Nevertheless, there is significant overlap between open source software and free software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite how it restricts its users, and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The FSF said that the term open source fosters an ambiguity of a different kind such that it confuses the mere availability of the source with the freedom to use, modify, and redistribute it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] On the other hand, the term free software was criticized for the ambiguity of the word free, which was seen as discouraging for business adoption, and for the historical ambiguous usage of the term.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Developers have used the alternative terms *Free and Open Source Software* (FOSS), or *Free/Libre and Open Source Software* (FLOSS), consequently, to describe open-source software that is also free software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Software can be distributed with source code, which is a code that is readable.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Software is source available when this source code is available to be seen.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However to be source available or FOSS, the source code does not need to be accessible to all, just the users of that software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] While all FOSS software is source available because this is a requirement made by the Open Source Definition, not all source available software is FOSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For example, if the software does not meet other aspects of the Open Source Definition such as permitted modification or redistribution, even if the source code is available, the software is not FOSS.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] A recent trend within software companies is open-sourcing, or transitioning their previous proprietary software into open-source software through releasing it under an open-source license.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Examples of companies who have done this are Google, Microsoft and Apple.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Additionally, open-sourcing can refer to programming open-source software or installing open-source software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open-sourcing can be beneficial in multiple ways, such as attracting more external contributors who bring new perspectives and problem solving capabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The downsides of open-sourcing include the work that has to be done to maintaining the new community, such as making the base code easily understandable, setting up communication channels for new developers and creating documentation to allow new developers to easily join.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, a review of several open-sourced projects found that although a newly open-sourced project attracts many newcomers, a great amount are likely to soon leave the project and their forks are also likely to not be impactful.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Other concepts that may share some similarities to open source are shareware, public domain software, freeware, and software viewers/readers that are freely available but do not provide source code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, these differ from open source software in access to source code, licensing, copyright and fees.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Despite being able to collaborate internationally, open source software contributors were found to mostly be located in large clusters such as Silicon Valley that largely collaborate within themselves.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Possible reasons for this phenomenon may be that the OSS contributor demographic largely works in software, meaning that the OSS geographic location is closely related to that dispersion and collaborations could be encouraged through work and social networks.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Code acceptance can be impacted by status within these social network clusters, creating unfair predispositions in code acceptance based on location.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Barriers to international collaboration also include linguistic or cultural differences.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Furthermore, each country has been shown to have a higher acceptance rate for code from contributors within their country except India, indicating a bias for culturally similar collaborators.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In 2021, the countries with the highest open source software contributions included the United States, China, Germany, India, and the UK, in that order.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The countries with the highest OSS developers per capita from a study in 2021 include, in order, Iceland, Switzerland, Norway, Sweden, and Finland, while in 2008 the countries with top amount of estimated contributors in SourceForge were the United States, Germany, United Kingdom, Canada and France.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Though there have been several studies done on the distribution and contributions of OSS developers, this is still an open field that can be measured in several different ways.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For instance, Information and communication technology participation, population, wealth and proportion of access to the internet have been shown to be correlated with OSS contributions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Although gender diversity has been found to enhance team productivity, women still face biases while contributing to open source software projects when their gender is identifiable.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In 2002, only 1.5% of international open-source software developers were women, while women made up 28% of tech industry roles, demonstrating their low representation in the software field.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, a more recent figure of female OSS participation internationally calculated across 2005 to 2021 is 9.8%, with most being recent contributors, indicating that female participation may be growing.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Contributors to OSS are motivated by belief in FOSS philosophy, personal interests, caring about the community, interest in projects and problem-solving, etc.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] In addition, users of a given software may also contribute as a way of improving tools they use, while others are drawn to the collaborative nature of open-source development environments.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Also, engagement with active projects allow contributors to stay current with industry practices and emerging trends.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The open source projects include the innovations and trends and they make it popular within the tech field.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Contributing to OSS can also increase a contributor's visibility and reputation within the community, as contributions are publicly accessible and can be reviewed by others.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] As a result, thousands of contributors daily contribute to the open source projects and help maintain it for the improvement of general public.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Even though programming was originally seen as a female profession, there remains a large gap in computing.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Social identity tends to be a large concern as women in the tech industry face insecurity about attracting unwanted male attention and harassment or being unfeminine in their technology knowledge, having a large impact on confidence.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Some male tech participants make clear that they believe women fitting in within the culture is impossible, furthering the insecurity for women and their place in the tech industry.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Additionally, even in a voluntary contribution environment like open source software, women tend to end up doing the less technical aspects of projects, such as manual testing or documentation despite women and men showing the same productivity in OSS contributions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Explicit biases include longer feedback time, more scrutinization of code and lower acceptance rate of code.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Specifically in the open-source software community, women report that sexually offensive language is common and the women's identity as female is given more attention that as an OSS contributor.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Bias is hard to address due to the belief that gender should not matter, with most contributors feeling that women getting special treatment is unfair and success should be dependent on skill, preventing any changes to be more inclusive.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open source software projects are built and maintained by a network of programmers, who may often be volunteers, and are widely used in free as well as commercial products.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] While the term open source applied originally only to the source code of software, it is now being applied to many other areas such as open-source ecology, a movement to decentralize technologies so that any human can use them.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] However, it is often misapplied to other areas that have different and competing principles, which overlap only partially.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The same principles that underlie open-source software can be found in many other ventures, such as open source, open content, and open collaboration.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] This "culture" or ideology takes the view that the principles apply more generally to facilitate concurrent input of different agendas, approaches, and priorities, in contrast with more centralized models of development such as those typically used in commercial companies.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] More than 90 percent of companies use open-source software as a component of their proprietary software.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] The decision to use open-source software, or even engage with open-source projects to improve existing open-source software, is typically a pragmatic business decision.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] When proprietary software is in direct competition with an open-source alternative, research has found conflicting results on the effect of the competition on the proprietary product's price and quality.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] For decades, some companies have made servicing of an open-source software product for enterprise users their business model.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] These companies control an open-source software product, and instead of charging for licensing or use, charge for improvements, integration, and other servicing.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Software as a service (SaaS) products based on open-source components are increasingly common.
[src:software-composition-analysis/open-source-software] Open-source software is preferred for scientific applications, because it increases transparency and aids in the validation and acceptance of scientific results.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] A **software supply chain** is the components, libraries, tools, and processes used to develop, build, and publish a software artifact.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] A **software bill of materials** (**SBOM**) declares the inventory of components used to build a software artifact, including any open source and proprietary software components.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] It is the software analogue to the traditional manufacturing BOM, which is used as part of supply chain management.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] SBOMs are a strategy for improving transparency in the software supply chain.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Software supply chain attacks compromise an upstream component — such as a widely-used library, a build tool, or a distribution channel — in order to simultaneously affect all downstream users of that component.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] High-profile incidents such as the SolarWinds attack illustrated the scale and reach of such attacks.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Researchers have catalogued the attack surface into a taxonomy covering all stages from source-code contribution to package distribution, linking attack vectors to real-world incidents and corresponding safeguards.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Another important concept in software supply chains is provenance: signed attestations can record where a software artifact came from, which source and dependencies were used, and which steps in the build pipeline produced it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Provenance frameworks such as in-toto help downstream users verify that a release was built by an expected process and help detect tampering between source retrieval, build, and distribution.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] An SBOM allows builders to make sure open-source and third-party software components are up to date and respond quickly to new vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Buyers and other stakeholders can use an SBOM to perform vulnerability or license analysis, which can be used to evaluate and manage risk in a product.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] While many companies use a spreadsheet for general BOM management, there are additional risks and issues in an SBOM written to a spreadsheet, such as the inability to automatically enrich it with vulnerability data or integrate it into security toolchains.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] It is best practice for SBOMs to be collectively stored in a repository that can be part of other automation systems and easily queried by other applications.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Cybersecurity transparency studies, including TRACS 2025, identify the availability of SBOMs as one of the criteria used when purchasing information security solutions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] However, not all enterprise security products provide publicly available SBOMs.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Research on open-source ecosystems indicates that policy-driven SBOMs remain rare in practice: one large-scale study found that only about 0.56% of popular GitHub repositories contain SBOMs created in accordance with formal security or compliance policies.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] Also, according to other research, fewer than half of tested software projects include SBOMs in their releases, and many of those SBOMs are incomplete or do not fully conform to established standards.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] At the same time, corporate-level surveys report that approximately 60–76 % of enterprises require SBOMs from suppliers or have integrated SBOMs into procurement and supply-chain risk management processes.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] US President Joe Biden’s **Executive Order 14028 on Improving the Nation’s Cybersecurity** of May 12, 2021 ordered NIST and NTIA to lay down guidelines for software supply chain management, including for SBOMs.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-bill-of-materials] The "automation support" requirement specifies the need for "automatic generation," which is possible with the use of Software Composition Analysis (SCA) solutions.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] It is a common software engineering practice to develop software by using different components.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Using software components segments the complexity of larger elements into smaller pieces of code and increases flexibility by enabling easier reuse of components to address new requirements.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] The practice has widely expanded since the late 1990s with the popularization of open-source software (OSS) to help speed up the software development process and reduce time to market.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] However, using open-source software introduces many risks for the software applications being developed.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Shortly after the foundation of the Open Source Initiative in February 1998, the risks associated with OSS were raised and organizations tried to manage this using spreadsheets and documents to track all the open source components used by their developers.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] For organizations using open-source components extensively, there was a need to help automate the analysis and management of open source risk.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] This resulted in a new category of software products called Software Composition Analysis (SCA) which helps organizations manage open source risk.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] SCA strives to detect all the 3rd party components in use within a software application to help reduce risks associated with security vulnerabilities, IP licensing requirements, and obsolescence of components being used.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Vulnerable method analysis addresses the problem of determining whether a vulnerability in a third-party library poses an actual risk to an application.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Rather than simply detecting the presence of vulnerable libraries, this technique analyzes whether the specific vulnerable methods within those libraries are reachable from the application's execution paths.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] The method was invented and first implemented at SourceClear under the leadership of Asankhaya Sharma between 2015 and 2017.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] The approach involves constructing call graphs that map the relationships between application code and library methods, then determining if there exists a path from application entry points to vulnerability-specific sinks in the libraries.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Traditional vulnerability databases rely on manual curation by security researchers, which can be time-intensive and may miss relevant vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Machine learning approaches automate this process by training models to predict whether data items from various sources (such as bug reports, commits, and mailing lists) are vulnerability-related.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] These systems implement complete pipelines from data collection through model training and prediction, with iterative improvement mechanisms that generate better models as new data becomes available.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] As SCA tools increasingly recommend library updates to address vulnerabilities, ensuring compatibility becomes critical.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Advanced static analysis techniques can automatically detect API incompatibilities that would be introduced by library upgrades, enabling automated vulnerability remediation without breaking existing functionality.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] These lightweight analyses are designed to integrate into continuous integration and continuous delivery pipelines.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] As SCA impacts different functions in organizations, different teams may use the data depending on the organization's corporation size and structure.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] The IT department will often use SCA for implementing and operationalizing the technology with common stakeholders including the chief information officer (CIO), the Chief Technology Officer (CTO), and the Chief Enterprise Architects (EA).
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Security and license data are often used by roles such as Chief Information Security Officers (CISO) for security risks, and Chief IP / Compliance officer for Intellectual Property risk management.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Depending on the SCA product capabilities, it can be implemented directly within a developer's Integrated Development Environment (IDE) who uses and integrates OSS components, or it can be implemented as a dedicated step in the software quality control process.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] SCA products, and particularly their capacity to generate an SBOM is required in some countries such as the United States to enforce the security of software delivered to one of their agencies by a vendor.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Another common use case for SCA is for Technology Due diligence.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Prior to a Merger & Acquisition (M&A) transaction, Advisory firms review the risks associated with the software of the target firm.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] The automatic nature of SCA products is their primary strength.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Developers don't have to manually do an extra work when using and integrating OSS components.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] The automation also applies to indirect references to other OSS components within code and artifacts.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Modern SCA implementations have significantly improved accuracy through advanced analysis techniques.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] Vulnerable method analysis reduces false positives by determining actual reachability of vulnerable code paths, while machine learning approaches for vulnerability curation help maintain more comprehensive and up-to-date vulnerability databases.
[src:software-composition-analysis/software-composition-analysis] These advances address many traditional limitations of metadata-only approaches.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] A **vulnerability database** (**VDB**) is a platform aimed at collecting, maintaining, and disseminating information about discovered computer security vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The database will customarily describe the identified vulnerability, assess the potential impact on affected systems, and any workarounds or updates to mitigate the issue.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] A VDB will assign a unique identifier to each vulnerability cataloged such as a number (e.g.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] 123456) or alphanumeric designation (e.g.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Information in the database can be made available via web pages, exports, or API.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] A VDB can provide the information for free, for pay, or a combination thereof.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The first vulnerability database was the "Repaired Security Bugs in Multics", published by February 7, 1973 by Jerome H.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] He described the list as "*a list of all known ways in which a user may break down or circumvent the protection mechanisms of Multics*".
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The list was initially kept somewhat private with the intent of keeping vulnerability details until solutions could be made available.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The published list contained two local privilege escalation vulnerabilities and three local denial of service attacks.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Major vulnerability databases such as the ISS X-Force database, Symantec / SecurityFocus BID database, and the Open Source Vulnerability Database (OSVDB) aggregate a broad range of publicly disclosed vulnerabilities, including Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE).
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The primary purpose of CVE, run by MITRE, is to attempt to aggregate public vulnerabilities and give them a standardized format unique identifier.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Many vulnerability databases develop the received intelligence from CVE and investigate further providing vulnerability risk scores, impact ratings, and the requisite workaround.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] In the past, CVE was paramount for linking vulnerability databases so critical patches and debugs can be shared to inhibit hackers from accessing sensitive information on private systems.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The National Vulnerability Database (NVD), run by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), is operated separately from the MITRE-run CVE database, but only includes vulnerability information from CVE.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] NVD serves as an enhancement to that data by providing Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) risk scoring and Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) data.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The Open Source Vulnerability Database provides an accurate, technical and unbiased index on vulnerability security.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The comprehensive database cataloged over 121,000 vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The OSVDB was founded in August 2002 and was launched in March 2004.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] In its primitive beginning, newly identified vulnerabilities were investigated by site members and explanations were detailed on the website.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] However, as the necessity for the service thrived, the need for dedicated staff resulted in the inception of the Open Security Foundation (OSF) which was founded as a non-profit organisation in 2005 to provide funding for security projects and primarily the OSVDB.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] National Vulnerability Database is a comprehensive cyber security vulnerability database formed in 2005 that reports on CVE.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The NVD is a primary cyber security referral tool for individuals and industries alike providing informative resources on current vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The NVD holds in excess of 100,000 records.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Similar to the OSVDB, the NVD publishes impact ratings and categorises material into an index to provide users with an intelligible search system.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Other countries have their own vulnerability databases, such as the Chinese National Vulnerability Database and Russia's Data Security Threats Database.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] A variety of commercial companies also maintain their own vulnerability databases, offering customers services which deliver new and updated vulnerability data in machine-readable format as well as through web portals.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Syndicate's Exploit Observer, Symantec's DeepSight portal and vulnerability data feed, Secunia's (purchased by Flexera) vulnerability manager and Accenture's vulnerability intelligence service (formerly iDefense).
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Exploit Observer uses its Vulnerability & Exploit Data Aggregation System (VEDAS) to collect exploits & vulnerabilities from a wide array of global sources, including Chinese and Russian databases.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Vulnerability databases advise organisations to develop, prioritize, and execute patches or other mitigations which attempt to rectify critical vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] However, this can often lead to the creation of additional susceptibilities as patches are created hastily to thwart further system exploitations and violations.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Depending upon the level of a user or organisation, they warrant appropriate access to a vulnerability database which provides the user with disclosure of known vulnerabilities that may affect them.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The justification for limiting access to individuals is to impede hackers from being versed in corporation system vulnerabilities which could potentially be further exploited.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Vulnerability databases contain a vast array of identified vulnerabilities.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] However, few organisations possess the expertise, staff, and time to revise and remedy all potential system susceptibilities hence vulnerability scoring is a method of quantitatively determining the severity of a system violation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] A multitude of scoring methods exist across vulnerability databases such as US-CERT and SANS Institute's Critical Vulnerability Analysis Scale but the Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) is the prevailing technique for most vulnerability databases including OSVDB, vFeed and NVD.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The CVSS is based upon three primary metrics: base, temporal and environmental which each provide a vulnerability rating.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] This metric covers the immutable properties of a vulnerability such as the potential impact of the exposure of confidential information, the accessibility of information and the aftermath of the irretrievable deletion of information.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The temporal metrics denote the mutable nature of a vulnerability for example the credibility of an exploitability, the current state of a system violation and the development of any workarounds that could be applied.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] This aspect of the CVSS rates the potential loss to individuals or organisations from a vulnerability.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Furthermore, it details the primary target of a vulnerability ranging from personal systems to large organisations and the number of potentially affected individuals.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The complication with utilising different scoring systems it that there is no consensus on the severity of a vulnerability thus different organisations may overlook critical system exploitations.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The key benefit of a standardised scoring system like CVSS is that published vulnerability scores can be assessed, pursued and remedied rapidly.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Organisations and individuals alike can determine the personal impact of a vulnerability on their system.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The benefits derived from vulnerability databases to consumers and organisations are exponential as information systems become increasingly embedded, our dependency and reliance on them grows, as does the opportunity for data exploitation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Although the functionality of a database may appear unblemished, without rigorous testing, the exiguous flaws can allow hackers to infiltrate a system's cyber security.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Frequently, databases are published without stringent security controls hence the sensitive material is easily accessible.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Database attacks are the most recurrent form of cyber security breaches recorded on vulnerability databases.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] SQL and NoSQL injections penetrate traditional information systems and big data platforms respectively and interpolate malicious statements allowing the hackers unregulated system access.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Established databases ordinarily fail to implement crucial patches suggested by vulnerability databases due to an excessive workload and the necessity for exhaustive trialling to ensure the patches update the defective system vulnerability.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Database operators concentrate their efforts into major system deficiencies which offers hackers unmitigated system access through neglected patches.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] All databases require audit tracks to record when data is amended or accessed.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] When systems are created without the necessary auditing system, the exploitation of system vulnerabilities are challenging to identify and resolve.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Vulnerability databases promulgate the significance of audit tracking as a deterrent of cyber attacks.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Data protection is essential to any business as personal and financial information is a key asset and the purloining of sensitive material can discredit the reputation of a firm.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] The implementation of data protection strategies is imperative to guard confidential information.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] Some hold the view that is it the initial apathy of software designers that in turn, necessitates the existence of vulnerability databases.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerability-database] If systems were devised with greater diligence, they may be impenetrable from SQL and NoSQL injections making vulnerability databases redundant.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The objective of the cheat sheet is to provide a proposal of approach regarding the handling of vulnerable third-party dependencies when they are detected, and this, depending on different situation.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Proposals mentioned in this cheat sheet are not silver-bullet (recipes that work in all situations) yet can be used as a foundation and adapted to your context.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Most of the projects use third-party dependencies to delegate handling of different kind of operations, *e.g.* generation of document in a specific format, HTTP communications, data parsing of a specific format, etc.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's a good approach because it allows the development team to focus on the real application code supporting the expected business feature.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The dependency brings forth an expected downside where the security posture of the real application is now resting on it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's highly recommended to perform automated analysis of the dependencies from the birth of the project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Indeed, if this task is added at the middle or end of the project, it can imply a huge amount of work to handle all the issues identified and that will in turn impose a huge burden on the development team and might to blocking the advancement of the project at hand.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In the rest of the cheat sheet, when we refer to *development team* then we assume that the team contains a member with the required application security skills or can refer to someone in the company having these kind of skills to analyse the vulnerability impacting the dependency.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's important to keep in mind the different ways in which a security issue is handled after its discovery.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here, the vulnerability is always referenced in the CVE global database used, generally, by the detection tools as one of the several input sources used.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] See a description here, into the section named **Computers** about **Computer Security**.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The researcher decides to release all the information including exploitation code/method on services like Full Disclosure mailing list, Exploit-DB.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here a CVE is not always created then the vulnerability is not always in the CVE global database causing the detection tools to be potentially blind about unless the tools use other input sources.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, it's possible to decide to accept the risk represented by the security issue.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] However, this decision must be taken by the Chief Risk Officer (fallback possible to Chief Information Security Officer) of the company based on technical feedback from the development team that have analyzed the issue (see the *Cases* section) as well as the CVEs CVSS score indicators.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, the development team can meet one of the situations (named *Case* in the rest of the cheat sheet) presented in the sub sections below.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the vulnerably impact a transitive dependency then the action will be taken on the direct dependency of the project because acting on a transitive dependency often impact the stability of the application.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Acting on a on a transitive dependency require the development team to fully understand the complete relation/communication/usage from the project first level dependency until the dependency impacted by the security vulnerability, this task is very time consuming.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Patched version of the component has been released by the provider.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests exist for the features of the application using the impacted dependency allowing to validate that the feature is operational.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Update the version of the dependency in the project on a testing environment.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that it will take a while to fix the issue and, so, a patched version will not be available before months.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If a workaround is provided, it should be applied and validated on the testing environment, and thereafter deployed to production.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has given the team a list of the impacted functions, protective code must wrap the calls to these functions to ensure that the input and the output data is safe.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Moreover, security devices, such as the Web Application Firewall (WAF), can handle such issues by protecting the internal applications through parameter validation and by generating detection rules for those specific libraries.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Yet, in this cheat sheet, the focus is set on the application level in order to patch the vulnerability as close as possible to the source.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided nothing about the vulnerability, Case 3 can be applied skipping the *step 2* of this case.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] We assume here that, at least, the CVE has been provided.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided the team with the exploitation code, and the team made a security wrapper around the vulnerable library/code, execute the exploitation code in order to ensure that the library is now secure and doesn't affect the application.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exist for the application, run them to verify that the protection code added does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Add a comment in the project *README* explaining that the issue (specify the related CVE) is handled during the waiting time of a patched version because the detection tool will continue to raise an alert on this dependency.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that they cannot fix the issue, so no patched version will be released at all (applies also if provider does not want to fix the issue or does not answer at all).
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In this case the only information given to the development team is the CVE.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Nothing specific because here we are in a *patch yourself* condition.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In all cases, here, we need to handle the vulnerability right now.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] As we know the vulnerable dependency, we know where it is used in the application (if it's a transitive dependency then we can identify the first level dependency using it using the IDE built-in feature or the dependency management system used (Maven, Gradle, NuGet, npm, etc.).
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Note that IDE is also used to identify the calls to the dependency.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying calls to this dependency is fine but it is the first step.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team still lacks information on what kind of patching needs to be performed.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] To obtain these information, the team uses the CVE content to know which kind of vulnerability affects the dependency.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The `description` property provides the answer: SQL injection, Remote Code Execution, Cross-Site Scripting, Cross-Site Request Forgery, etc.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] After identifying the above 2 points, the team is aware of the type of patching that needs to be taken (Case 2 with the protective code) and where to add it.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team has an application using the Jackson API in a version exposed to the CVE-2016-3720.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Based on these information, the team determines that the necessary patching will be to add a pre-validation of any XML data passed to the Jakson API to prevent XML external entity (XXE) vulnerability.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If possible, create a unit test that mimics the vulnerability in order to ensure that the patch is effective and have a way to continuously ensure that the patch is in place during the evolution of the project.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exists for the application then run them to verify that the patch does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider collaborates with you after being notified of the vulnerability.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Inform the provider about the vulnerability by sharing the post with them.
[src:software-composition-analysis/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] This section lists several tools that can used to analyze the dependencies used by a project in order to detect the vulnerabilities.
